# migrated from tests/cases/rulespec.chat (gen346, hermetic + isolated)
[mock hermetic]
!set PARROT0_BASE=
!set PARROT0_SESSION=
!set PARROT0_WORLD_FACTS=0
!set PARROT0_LANG=en
!reset

[test rulespec]
# gen265 (the first RULESCORE pull): a rules-spec implementation request is
# recognized as a CATEGORY and answered honestly — parrot0 reports what it DID
# understand (title, numbered-rule count, which rule classes appear: input /
# state / end) and declines the translation naming the F4 text->code gap.
# Before this, chitchat/pragma MISCLAIMED these specs ("Ha, you're playful!"),
# and a misclaim is worse than a wall (gen254). The form (ordered numbered
# markers, paragraph length) is structural; every word class is an
# intent_cue(...) fact in kb/core/intents.p0 — teachable at runtime.
> Coin Duel. Rules: 1. Each round the player types h or t. 2. On a match the score increases by one point. 3. The game ends when the score reaches three and prints WIN. Implement this game as one complete C program for the terminal.
< That is a rules spec — "Coin Duel", 3 numbered rules; I can recognize the input, state and end rules, but I cannot yet translate free-text rules into a program. My code synthesis covers verified schemas (a sort from a learned shape, arithmetic composition), not open rule specs — the text-to-code bridge is the gap.

# a different surface: parenthesis markers, no title line, "write this game"
> You start with 10 tokens. 1) each turn you enter a number from 1 to 3 and lose that many tokens. 2) if your total reaches exactly zero you win. 3) when tokens go below zero the game ends and you lose. Write this game in C.
< That is a rules spec — "You start with 10 tokens", 3 numbered rules; I can recognize the input, state and end rules, but I cannot yet translate free-text rules into a program. My code synthesis covers verified schemas (a sort from a learned shape, arithmetic composition), not open rule specs — the text-to-code bridge is the gap.

# gen266: the FIRST synthesized category — count_to_threshold. The rules name
# the scoring token (rule_gain + rule_input cues), the threshold (rule_reach +
# a number word) and the final word (rule_print, case kept from the raw); the
# schema is a game_shape KB fact; the emitted program is DISPOSED by the
# run-grounded oracle (3 hits must print VICTORY, 2 must not) before parrot0
# presents it. Coin Duel above still declines: its "match" semantics are not
# expressible — the category is honest about its border.
# gen269: the reply is MULTI-LINE — verdict first, then the program in a
# markdown ```c fence with real indentation (opencode/pi clients render it as
# code). The harness matches line-by-line: consecutive '<' lines are one reply.
> Key Tally. Rules: 1. Each round the player types a single word. 2. When the player types win the score increases by one point. 3. The game ends when the score reaches three and prints VICTORY. Implement this game as one complete C program for the terminal.
< Verified by execution: 3 "win" inputs print VICTORY and 2 do not (count_to_threshold schema, two scripted plays via the counter-game oracle).
<
< ```c
< #include <stdio.h>
< #include <string.h>
<
< int main(void) {
<     char t[64];
<     const char *w = "win";
<     int s = 0;
<     while (s < 3 && scanf("%63s", t) == 1) {
<         if (strcmp(t, w) == 0)
<             s++;
<     }
<     if (s >= 3)
<         printf("VICTORY\n");
<     return 0;
< }
< ```

# negative control: numbered arithmetic is NOT a spec (no request cue)
> what is 1. plus 2.
< 3.

